column1: Who will Hillary Clinton pick as her vice presidential running mate?
column5: ['Cory Booker', 'Sherrod Brown', 'Julian Castro', 'Timothy Kaine', 'Elizabeth Warren', 'Someone else']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
column11: This question was closed with the answer "Timothy Kaine" on 25 July 2016 with an end date of 22 July 2016. On 22 July 2016, Hillary Clinton announced via a tweet to her supporters that Tim Kaine would be her vice presidential running mate (CNN, NY Times). The Clinton campaign has begun vetting potential vice presidential candidates (Washington Post, NBC News, Voice of America, NBC News). Recommended Questions Who will win the 2016 US presidential election? Will Donald Trump pick one of the former candidates for the Republican nomination as his vice presidential running mate?

After reading other's comments re Sherrod Brown's Democratic Senate seat being filled by a Republican governor, I downgraded my estimate for Brown and added those points to Tim Kaine, a good "safe" pick for Hillary, but not electrifying like Warren.

Kaine is the most likely because he has no downside other than blandness. A senator that would be replaced by a Democratic governor. Warren is popular and her selection would result in a quick election for her replacement by Massachusetts law. Booker is the strongest personal pick in many ways, but would be replaced by a Republican's selection, making him not ideal. Brown is in the same boat while being politically attractive but not personally attractive to Clinton (is my instinct). Casto is neither attractive nor plausible by resume. Someone else is fairly strong because no one listed is a slam dunk (and contains the rest of the population).

Kaine appears to be the consensus “safe” choice, while Warren appears to be the consensus risky choice. Per @alanne (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/277551), Warren vacating her senate seat would lead to a Republican taking her place.

I think we underestimate Castro. HCR launched her bid for Senate after her then President husband pardoned the PR separatists, and in their long game - Castro would be in line for the White House after a 8 year share of a second Clinton Presidency. It would also solidify the voting bloc behind the Dems and defend against inroads on that bloc by the Republicans over that same eight year time frame and help deliver big Senate seats to her as well.

Taking a big risk on this question. Don't know anything about the people listed here, but GJO consensus is that it is either EW and TK. Also, I think HRC is less likely to spring a surprise on the voters with the VP nominee than Trump. Caution is that if Trump picks his VP first, she may be forced to pick a counter candidate which could still end up as a surprise. However, I think Trump is likely to pick his candidate later than HRC, which means HRC is likely to pick one of the leading 'known' contenders.

Surprisingly hard. There really isn't a standout nominee, when you consider the impact to the Senate. Both Warren and Brown would be replaced by Republican Senators (at least for a while). And this election is all about the Senate. The next President and Senate will change the Supreme Court for years to come. Thus, low probabilities for Warren and Brown. Castro is good, but he helps lock up Hispanics and other minorities that Clinton already has locked up. As mentioned in the Huff Post article below, Kaine is a "do no harm" (i.e., be cautious) candidate, and that is the definition of the Clinton race. I think it will be Kaine.

Great finally to see this question. Fun no matter what the scoring is. Only two real contributions. JC's actual resume (even if possible past scandals are a non-issue) is a bit weak. Second, Cokey Roberts (NPR) opined recently that a woman as VP would trigger negative reactions (bias even if subtle) toward women at the top of the ticket. If not for that aspect which I would not have considered beforehand, I'd have EW higher.

These are all pretty good people, as is Mark Warner, who isn't on the list and so is my "someone else" avatar. I think she needs geographic support rather than demographic. She will do well among blacks, Hispanics, and women no matter what. She will carry Jersey and Massachusetts no matter what, and will not carry Texas no matter what. Brown is well regarded and well connected in Ohio, always a swing state and this year maybe more than ever, and Kaine is from Virginia, which should be close but will probably go for Clinton anyway.
